rs. One important factor are charges and recurring fees. Those charges and fees can be</p><ul> <li>Annual account maintenance fee;</li> <li>Currency conversion fee;</li> <li>ATM withdrawal fee;</li> <li>Online transfer, overdraft, wire transfer;</li> <li>Fall below fee if the account balance is lower than the minimum requirement.</li> </ul><h3 class="indexed"><span id="high-risk-activities" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">7.2.</span> <span class="heading_text">High-risk activities</span></h3><p>Banks will <a href="../frozen-bank-account.html">freeze accounts</a> if they notice unusual transactions, like large deposits or international transfers from unknown sources, as a precaution against fraud.Â </p><p><strong>Solution</strong></p><p>To prevent this, inform your bank if youâ€™re expecting high activity or significant transactions, and have documentation ready if needed.Â </p><p>If your financial activities change, consider talking to your bank about adjusting transaction limits. This communication helps keep transactions smooth and avoids interruptions, especially useful for handling multi-currency or international payments effectively.</p><h3 class="indexed"><span id="avoid-trading-with-high-risk-countries" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">7.3.</span> <span class="heading_text">Avoid trading with high-risk countries</span></h3><p>To avoid account freezes, itâ€™s also crucial not to trade with sanctioned or high-risk countries, like those under international sanctions, as these transactions often trigger banking restrictions.Â </p><p>Avoid high-risk activities, such as handling enormous sums without obvious sources or sending frequent, high-value transfers to multiple new recipients, as these can raise red flags.</p><p><strong>Solution</strong></p><ul> <li>Track transactions: Maintain records of all your transactions, particularly for business accounts, to verify any flagged activity.</li> <li>Know your transfer partners: Only 